====Related terms====
* {{ja-r|この}} [[this]]
* {{ja-r|その}} [[that]] (near listener)
* {{ja-r|どの}} [[which]]
* {{ja-r|あれ}} [[that]] one over there (far from speaker and listener)
* {{ja-r|あそこ}} that direction over there

====Usage notes====
* あの is also used to refer to things and experiences that both the speaker and the listener have knowledge of. Compare the two following sentences,
*: {{ja-usex|'''あの'''本はやすいですか？|'''あの''' ほん は やすい です か？|Is that book (over there, which you and I can see) cheap?}}
*: {{ja-usex|'''その'''本はやすいですか？|'''その''' ほん は やすい です か？|Is that book (I'm pointing to/near you/of yours) cheap? / Is that book which you (have/saw/were talking about) cheap?}}
* The hiragana spelling ([[あの]]) is preferred to the kanji spelling ([[彼の]]), which is rarely used.

===Interjection===
{{ja-pos|interjection}}

# similar to English {{term|lang=en|er}} or {{term|lang=en|umm}}, said when [[hesitating]] in speech
# similar to English {{term|lang=en|uh}}, space [[filler]] or [[pause]] during conversation
#: '''あの'''…そうですね、…
#: '''um'''... well, yes,...

====Related terms====
* {{ja-l|ええと}}, {{ja-r|えーと}}: oh, well, er, um

====Usage notes====
The {{ja-r|の}} sound is often lengthened as in {{ja-l|あのう}}, {{ja-l|あのぉ}}, {{ja-r|あのー}}.

